50|$|The Pluma <b>porgy</b> {{is similar}} to its relative, the Jolthead <b>porgy</b> (C. bajonado). However, it has fewer rays on its Pectoral fins than the Jolthead. The Pluma <b>porgy</b> has both 12 spines and 12 soft rays on its dorsal fin, while it has only 3 spines and 10 rays on its anal fin. Their heads are {{somewhat}} steep when viewed in profile, and have poorly developed prefrontal tubercles. The Pluma <b>porgy's</b> overall color is silvery with purple, or lavender iridescence, individual scales have brown-yellow edges with iridescent, blue-green spots.|$|R
50|$|<b>Porgy</b> and Bess, {{which came}} out in April 1959, {{is not to be}} {{confused}} with either the 1951 release by the same title or the 1956 release The Complete <b>Porgy</b> and Bess (which is also known as just <b>Porgy</b> and Bess too). All three albums draw on the material in George and Ira Gershwin's operatic stage drama of that name, a piece that had its original Broadway production in 1935. It should be noted as well that all of the above titles are also sometimes known as <b>Porgy</b> & Bess.|$|R
